items.body:
Might be a silly question but:

I'm trying to update to 2.1 from 1.0.1 but I haven't been able to access this script after installing the package. I couldn't find more documentation or troubleshooting for this utility and with my limited experience I haven't seen other packages provide scripts like this before. (the file is simply not added to $PATH). Am I missing some step?
(I could simply use the script from this repo but I wonder what to do to make it work the intended way).

...........

Yes: `scripts/fixup_keywords.py` is published with the library.

If you install the library it will be available on the command line. https://python-packaging.readthedocs.io/en/latest/command-line-scripts.html#the-scripts-keyword-argument

_Originally posted by @busunkim96 in https://github.com/googleapis/python-texttospeech/pull/30#discussion_r433498731_

labels.name: :rotating_light:
labels.description: This issue needs some love.

labels.name: api: texttospeech
labels.description: Issues related to the Cloud Text to Speech API API.

labels.name: priority: p1
labels.description: Medium priority. Will be fixed prior to next release.

labels.name: type: bug
labels.description: Error or flaw in code with unintended results or allowing sub-optimal usage patterns.

items.body:
I use Google Cloud App Engine standard environment Python 3.7.

My app has worked well, but today it gives me error suddenly.

This is an error message.
```
File "/srv/main.py", line 84, in synthesize
    input_text = texttospeech.types.SynthesisInput(ssml=ssml)
AttributeError: module 'google.cloud.texttospeech' has no attribute 'types'
```

I searched the Internet and found the solution in this stackoverflow post.
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/62523362/i-cant-seem-to-make-the-google-cloud-texttospeech-to-work

I could solve this error by downgrading the library (I modified requirements.txt)
"google-cloud-texttospeech<2.0.0"

I have 3 App Engine apps which uses this python-texttospeech library in the same way, but only one app causes the problem.

Why does this error happen? Should I modify other apps' requirements.txt?

This is the part of my app's code.
```
@app.route("/synthesize", methods=['POST', 'GET'])
def synthesize():
    if request.method == "POST":
        if request.form['Radio'] == 'normal':
            ssml = '<speak><prosody rate="slow">' + request.form['text'] + '</prosody></speak>'
        else:
            ssml = '<speak>' + request.form['text'] + '</speak>'    
            
        accent = request.form['accent']
        voiceid = next((voice for voice in request.form.getlist('voiceId[]') if accent in voice), None)
        os.environ["GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS"]="credentials.json"
 
        client = texttospeech.TextToSpeechClient()
        input_text = texttospeech.types.SynthesisInput(ssml=ssml)
        voice = texttospeech.types.VoiceSelectionParams(
            language_code=accent,
            name=voiceid)

        audio_config = texttospeech.types.AudioConfig(
            audio_encoding=texttospeech.enums.AudioEncoding.MP3)

        response = client.synthesize_speech(input_text, voice, audio_config)

        with open('/tmp/output.mp3', 'wb') as out:
            out.write(response.audio_content)

        return send_file("/tmp/output.mp3",as_attachment=True)
    else:
        return render_template("synthesize.html")
```

items.title: Google Cloud Function: No module named pip

labels.name: api: texttospeech
labels.description: Issues related to the Cloud Text to Speech API API.

labels.name: type: question
labels.description: Request for information or clarification. Not an issue.

items.body:
When attempting to use google.cloud's texttospeech module in a Google Cloud Functions, Python 3.7 Runtime, there is an error stating:

"""
Build failed: `pip_install_from_wheels` had stderr output:
/opt/python3.7/bin/python3.7: No module named pip

error: `pip_install_from_wheels` returned code: 1; Error ID: ECB5F712
"""

This occurs when google-cloud-texttospeech has been included in the requirements.txt, particularly when uploaded from a terminal, or when derived from a google cloud source repository.

#### Steps to reproduce

  1. Make a new folder with any example main.py + a requirements.txt that includes google-cloud-texttospeech
  2. Upload to a gcf: gcloud functions deploy my-python-function --entry-point helloworld --runtime python37 --trigger-http --allow-unauthenticated

#### Code example

def helloworld():
    return

This originally showed up when I was trying to use the Serverless framework. It works fine with the inline editor, but once a cloud repo is used it fails.

items.title: System tests were deleted in #30

labels.name: :rotating_light:
labels.description: This issue needs some love.

labels.name: api: texttospeech
labels.description: Issues related to the Cloud Text to Speech API API.

labels.name: triage me
labels.description: I really want to be triaged.

items.body:
The System tests as defined by the noxfile are broken and being skipped.

From one of the more recent CI runs (since #30 ), linked in [ResultStore](https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/395db6ca-dbbb-4c10-8114-11a4fa1d3ed5/targets/cloud-devrel%2Fclient-libraries%2Fpython%2Fgoogleapis%2Fpython-texttospeech%2Fcontinuous%2Fcontinuous/log): 


I see the following lines:

```
Running session system-3.7
Creating virtual environment (virtualenv) using python3.7 in .nox/system-3-7
Session system-3.7 skipped: System tests were not found.
```

and

```
Ran multiple sessions:
* lint: success
* blacken: success
* lint_setup_py: success
* unit-3.6: success
* unit-3.7: success
* unit-3.8: success
* system-3.7: skipped
* cover: success
* docs: success
```


The system tests are being skipped.

I believe this is because the decorator here:
https://github.com/googleapis/python-texttospeech/blob/b68df446daa7983cad1d31553ece6df569c932b2/noxfile.py#L94

requires a string if it is a single python environment. This is not clearly documented in the [Noxfile Docs](https://nox.thea.codes/en/stable/config.html#configuring-a-session-s-virtualenv) but it might be the case.

Before #30 , the decorator was given a list of two elements, but after #30,  `SYSTEM_TEST_PYTHON_VERSIONS=["3.7"]` . This could be changed to a string, and a comment added to point to the Noxfile docs, in case in the future, we want to test more Python versions.
